Anonymous Fri 10 Sep 2021 09:12:34 No.41532337 Report

Actually, let me break out two examples even further:
Barbarian rage in every edition is a buffed state that can be used a limited number of times per day. 4th represents this by making it a "daily" card that can be reused a number of times per day.
Wizards in every edition have a spread of spells and a limited stock of slots to prepare them in. 4th represents this by giving them multiple "daily" abilities per level and having you pick the one that you get to actually use per day, aka what you prepare into your spell slot.

The entire system was an exercise in putting existing concepts into a universal framework, and it failed not because it didn't do that, but because the players didn't want a unified and easy to work with framework but instead a complex and messy framework that they could feel intellectually superior for "beating". Also because the lead web designer committed a murder-suicide that scrapped massive parts of the planned digital rollout of the edition.
They just recycled a lot of it into 5e anyways, but in a patchwork way that only ever emphasized the flaws of 3.5 (because those flaws are exactly what people wanted). Casters getting unlimited cantrips? Artifact of at-will abilities. But for everyone else those variant basic attacks go back to being a feat tax, because fuck anyone who isn't playing a magic user with their reddit "I'm so smart so I should be the only person who matters in the game" mentality.
